  <!-- TIER 3: METHODOLOGY -->
  <div class="methodology" style="margin-top: 32px;">
    <div class="methodology-header" onclick="toggleMethodology()">
      <div class="methodology-header-left">
        <svg class="methodology-icon" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path d="M9 4.804A7.968 7.968 0 005.5 4c-1.255 0-2.443.29-3.5.804v10A7.969 7.969 0 015.5 14c1.669 0 3.218.51 4.5 1.385A7.962 7.962 0 0114.5 14c1.255 0 2.443.29 3.5.804v-10A7.968 7.968 0 0014.5 4c-1.255 0-2.443.29-3.5.804V12a1 1 0 11-2 0V4.804z"/></svg>
        <div>
          <div class="methodology-title">Calculation Methodology and Scope</div>
          <div class="methodology-sub">How this calculator works and what it accounts for</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="methodology-toggle" id="methToggleLabel">Show <span style="font-size:10px;margin-left:4px;">&#9660;</span></div>
    </div>
    <div class="methodology-body" id="methodologyBody">
      <h4>What This Calculator Models</h4>
      <p>This calculator models the <strong>annual cost of routine interval-based bump testing and calibration</strong> for a portable gas detection fleet. It compares your current testing regime against a risk-calibrated alternative based on the maintenance intervals validated for LEL MPS sensor technology: up to 30-day bump test intervals and up to 180-day calibration intervals under appropriate conditions.</p>
      <p>Costs are calculated across two dimensions: <strong>calibration gas consumption</strong> (cylinder volume, cost, and efficiency-adjusted usable volume per test) and <strong>technician labour</strong> (time per test event multiplied by fully-loaded hourly rate). Both dimensions are applied across the full fleet for the selected annual working period.</p>

      <h4>Cylinder Efficiency Factor</h4>
      <p>Cylinders are never fully exhausted in practice. Gas is lost during regulator connection and purging (typically 0.1–0.3L per connection event), and residual gas cannot be extracted once cylinder pressure drops below the regulator's minimum operating threshold (approximately 10–15% of cylinder volume). The efficiency factor — defaulted to 85% — adjusts the usable cylinder volume to reflect real-world conditions rather than theoretical capacity.</p>

      <h4>Calibration Gas Volume Ratio</h4>
      <p>Full calibration events consume more gas than bump tests due to the longer exposure time required to establish an accurate reference point. The calculator applies a <strong>3x multiplier</strong> to the bump test gas volume for calibration events. This is a conservative estimate; actual consumption depends on your regulator flow rate, device sensor count, and calibration procedure duration.</p>

      <h4>What Is Excluded From This Model</h4>
      <p>This calculator deliberately excludes certain testing categories that are <strong>event-driven rather than interval-driven</strong>, and whose frequency depends on site-specific conditions that cannot be generalised:</p>
      <div class="methodology-tags">
        <span class="tag excluded">Pre-task testing (confined space entry)</span>
        <span class="tag excluded">Post-alarm retesting</span>
        <span class="tag excluded">Post over-limit event recalibration</span>
        <span class="tag excluded">Post under-limit event testing</span>
        <span class="tag excluded">Emergency response testing</span>
        <span class="tag excluded">Post-incident return-to-service</span>
      </div>
      <p style="margin-top:14px;">If confined space entry is entered in the refinement section, those tests are added to <strong>both scenarios equally</strong> — since pre-entry bump testing is a regulatory requirement regardless of sensor type or interval regime. This does not affect the saving calculation but produces a more accurate total cost picture.</p>

      <h4>What Is Included</h4>
      <div class="methodology-tags">
        <span class="tag included">Routine interval bump testing</span>
        <span class="tag included">Routine interval calibration</span>
        <span class="tag included">Cylinder gas cost (efficiency-adjusted)</span>
        <span class="tag included">Technician labour (fully-loaded)</span>
        <span class="tag included">Retest allowance (if selected)</span>
        <span class="tag included">Confined space pre-entry testing (additive)</span>
      </div>

      <h4>Scenario B: The Risk-Calibrated Alternative</h4>
      <p>Scenario B applies bump test intervals of up to 30 days and calibration intervals of up to 180 days. These intervals are based on manufacturer-validated performance data for LEL MPS sensors operating in low-to-medium risk diffused applications. They <strong>do not apply</strong> to confined space entry, IDLH environments, sites where sensor poisons are present, multi-gas devices where not all sensors are MPS-type, or any site where regulations or insurance requirements mandate more frequent testing.</p>

      <h4>Important Limitations</h4>
      <p>Results are estimates and should be treated as a starting point for internal discussion. Actual savings depend on negotiated gas pricing, specific device and regulator configurations, the mix of sensor types in your fleet, and applicable regulatory requirements in your jurisdiction. This tool does not constitute compliance guidance. Always apply the most stringent requirements applicable to your site and consult your safety officer before modifying any testing SOP.</p>
      <p>This calculator was developed by <strong>Blackline Safety</strong> in collaboration with Nevada Nano, manufacturer of the LEL MPS sensor. It reflects Blackline Safety's point of view on the relationship between sensor diagnostic capability and maintenance interval design.</p>
    </div>
